\section{Data understanding}
\subsection{Data Sources}
The main dataset used in this project was provided by Planwisely B.V. and consists 
of historical sales records from a Dutch confectionery manufacturer. The data is 
stored in CSV format and contains 42,625 daily sales entries, covering 1,027 
individual product SKUs and spanning from December 2017 to December 2021. Each 
record includes three fields: a product identifier, a sales date, and daily sales 
volume. The B2B wholesale nature of the data is reflected in the near-absence of 
sales records on weekends, indicating that downstream buyers are institutional 
clients rather than individual consumers.
\\
\\To enrich the predictive features, three types of external data were integrated. 
The first type is climate data from the Royal 
Netherlands Meteorological Institute (KNMI), including weekly average, maximum, and 
minimum temperatures, precipitation, and sunshine hours. The second type is Dutch 
public holiday data, extracted using the Python \texttt{holidays} library, covering 
major holidays such as Easter, King's Day, and Christmas. Holiday effects are known 
to cause sharp deviations in retail demand and are therefore important to include as 
features \citep{turkmen2021forecasting}. Features derived from this include the 
number of days until the nearest holiday and the distance to Easter. The third type 
is Dutch school holiday data, collected for the three educational regions of Noord, 
Midden, and Zuid, covering autumn, Christmas, spring, and summer breaks, to capture 
the influence of school holidays on consumer behaviour.
